      <h1>My Rise to Geekdom</h1>
    </header>

    <p>This story covers the nerdier aspects of my early life, leaving
       healthy activites such as sports, music and social interaction
       completely out of the picture.</p>

    <p><aside><img src="images/geekdom/flammable.png"
         alt="Putting the flammable symbol on liquids inspire great deeds"></aside>
       As a little nerdling I grew up with a fondness for the sciences;
       chemistry, mechanics and electronics. I liked taking things apart
       (not necessarily being able to put them back together) and managed
       a fair share of inventions of my own.</p>

    <p><aside><img src="images/geekdom/lego.jpg"
         alt="Lego, keeping the world supplied with engineers"></aside>
       My room was not nearly as accessible as my mother would have wanted,
       at one point I had a dozen pieces of string by my bed using which I
       could control most aspects of the surroundings. It is amazing what
       you can do with a few metres of string, tape and
       <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lego">Lego</a> blocks.</p>

    <p>I had an early fascination with television. Not the programming but
       the technology itself, the two channels available seldom catered to
       kids. I dreamt of being able to have my own shows on TV, to control
       what was being displayed.</p>

       <p><aside><img src="images/geekdom/coleco.jpg"
         alt="ColecoVision"></aside>
       A couple of the more special days of my childhood involved my father
       bringing home a magical black box. A thing of wondrous, exciting
       adventure. A rental
       <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Coleco_Vision">Coleco Vision</a>
       featuring classics such as
       <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Montezuma%27s_Revenge_(video_game)">Montezuma's Revenge</a>.
       <aside><img src="images/geekdom/progtvg.jpg"
         alt="The PTVG, a cheap copy of the SD 50"></aside>
       At one point we also had our own <a href="http://www.pong-story.com/sd050.htm">SD-050</a> based black and white
       system with not only controllers sharp enough to make your hands blead but also a
       <a href="http://www.pong-story.com/pc-50x.htm">PC-501</a> cartridge, giving us access to ten
       <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pong">Pong</a> derivatives, each
       mimicking a sport. These early gaming consoles gave me at least limited
       power over the TV.</p>

    <p><aside><img src="images/geekdom/c64.jpg"
         alt="Commodore - great engineer, bad management"></aside>
       Given a taste, I quested on. My brother had a friend with a
       <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/C64"><abbr title="Commodore Business Machines Model number 64">C=64</abbr></a>
       on which he showed me how to draw the Swedish flag. Complete control
       over the TV screen. The holy grail as it were.</p>

    <p>My father studied programming back in the days when <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Punchcards">punch cards</a>
       were all the rage and figured he could pass some of his wisdom on to me
       and my older brother. We became one of the first families in the
       neighbourhood with a
       <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/C128"><abbr title="Commodore Business Machines Model number 128">C=128</abbr></a>.
       Mind-boggling 128kB of memory and a new powerful version of
       <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/BASIC"><abbr title="Beginner's All-purpose Symbolic Instruction Code">BASIC</abbr></a>
       which had commands for drawing graphics.</p>

    <p>After a week of family time around
       <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Summer_Games">Summer Games</a> and
       <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Winter_Games">Winter Games</a>, I
       picked up the BASIC manual.
       <aside><img src="images/geekdom/bathandle.jpg"
         alt="Command Control Bat Handle Joystick - Best of the best"></aside>
       Two of my first games were <em>Baloon attack</em> and <em>Karate Kid</em>.
       The first was a two player game, one player dropping sand bags and the
       other armed with bow and arrows). The other game was loosely based on the
       Karate Kid movie. Since only my brother was old enough to see it, I had
       to make some assumptions. It ended up being a fight against a bull,
       using fists, kicks and throwing stars (having seen the movie in later
       years, it would seem my early assumptions were a bit flawed). In order
       to make better use of the graphics, I taught myself basic trigometry
       - a skill unexpectedly useful for impressing the ladies.</p>

    <p>This was not my first experience with BASIC. Cue
       <a href="http://tvtropes.org/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/FlashbackEffects">stereotypical flashback</a>.
       <aside><img src="images/geekdom/automan.jpg"
         alt="Automan - a show to love"></aside>
       There was one television show I got to see that has meant more to me
       than virtually any cultural expression since -
       <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Automan">Automan</a>. A desk
       copper named Walter manages to create a holographic projection of the
       perfect police officer using the station computer, draining the city
       power supply in the processes. Only recently having learned how to read,
       I went to the library. Imagine my disappointment when the BASIC book
       I found had no listing for holography in the index.</p>

    <p>Time passed and hardware upgrades rolled in. My parents will never
       forget the tears of joy brought on by a
       <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Commodore_1571"><abbr title="Commodore 1571 disk drive">1571</abbr></a> and an
       <a href="http://www.richardlagendijk.nl/cip/category/printer/mps_1000"><abbr title="Commodore MPS 1000 dot matrix printer">MPS 1000</abbr></a> on Christmas eve.</p>

    <p>Using my <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Final_Cartridge">Final Cartridge III</a>
       I got a taste for the
       <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Amiga_Workbench">Amiga Workbench</a>
       environment. It was also a great help introducing me to
       <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Machine_code">machine code</a>
       and later
       <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Assembly_language">assembler</a>
       programming. Using the built-in
       <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Machine_code_monitor">monitor</a>
       I borrowed scroll text and music player code and presented
       "Happy birthday" demos to proud parents.</p>

    <p><aside><img src="images/geekdom/amiga500.jpg"
         alt="Amiga 500 - a box ful of delicious chips"></aside>
       With my first real <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Amiga">Amiga</a>
       (a model 500), I expanded my programming skills to include C, systems
       programming and GUI development.
       I never made it big on the demo scene but made some contributions with
       friends (we managed a 64 pixel scroller within 5
       <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Amiga_Original_chipset#Copper">copper</a> lines!).</p>

