     <p>Keeping the Amiga for entertainment, I got myself a Blue Chip PC
        Popular XT 8088-2
        <aside><img src="images/geekdom/bluechip.jpg"
          alt="Blue Chip PC Popular XT"></aside>
        to get a system compatible with the setup at school. It featured
        a turbo button which could be used to toggle clock speeds between
        8Mhz and 4.77Mhz. Some application back then actually worked very
        poorly with the lightning fast speeds you got from 8Mhz.</p>

     <p>I spent most of by PC time hacking
        <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Turbo_pascal">Turbo Pascal</a>
        with embessed assembler, working myself through an early release of
        <a href="http://www.ctyme.com/rbrown.htm">Ralf Brown's Interrupt List</a>
        and Pascal snippets off the
        <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/FidoNet">FidoNet</a>
        equivalent of
        <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Usenet">Usenet</a>
        used before newfangled technologies such as web forums and blogs.
        By this time I got my first email address via a FidoNet gateway.
        Usually, a mail did not take more than a couple of nights to be
        delivered.</p>

     <p><aside><img src="images/geekdom/borland.svg"
       alt="Borland, makers of Delphi and Turbo Pascal"></aside>
        By the time I graduated and left for military service, I had upgraded to
        a system based on the 486 SX. With enough power to run Windows 3.11 and
        <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Delphi_programming_language">Delphi</a>
        I invested some time automating the tedious work at the garrison watch
        earning me a healthy infusion of cash.</p>

     <p>After demob I worked a few months to pass time before starting my
        first year at the university. This was also the last few months
        of active membership at the local computer club.</p>

     <p><a href="http://www.eagle.y.se/">Eagle computing</a> started off
        as an association called TGEH, The Graphic Equalizer Hackers. We
        rented a hall on saturdays once every month or so and got together
        and basically had what surmounted to a LAN party, only we used
        <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Floppynet">Floppynet</a>
        rather than
        <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ethernet">Ethernet</a>.
        <aside><img src="images/geekdom/rgb_lenses.jpg"
          alt="Red, green, and blue lenses. Attach to a video camera and *BLAMMO* - a color still image"></aside>
        People showed off demos and hardware hacks. I remember fondly my
        sitting 5 minutes in front of a video camera in order to get a
        digital image of myself on the Amiga. Keeping the eyes from
        blinking while scanning the lines where they were visible was a
        pain. </p>

     <p>Later on, we managed to rent a small place in which we keep a
        <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bulletin_board_system"><abbr title="Bulletin Board System">BBS</abbr></a>
        running, along with a few other machines. A place to hang out
        after school. We outgrew the place soon enough and got ourself
        a huge place - a garage complete with weird fluids coming out
        of the walls. <span class="noprint">Check out
        <a class="download" href="images/geekdom/jimmy_robert_mortis.jpg">this</a>
        image from the restoration project (I am the one jumping in the back).</span></p>

     <p>Having a big place allowed us to move in more hardware. We got
        a pretty large collection of
        <aside><img src="images/geekdom/digital.png"
          alt="Digital Equipment Corporation"></aside>
        <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Digital_Equipment_Corporation">DEC</a>
        boxen such as
        <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/VAX">VAX</a> machines running
        <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ultrix">Ultrix</a>, a UNIX
        variant. I think we even had a
        <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Programmed_Data_Processor">PDP-11</a>
        at one point.</p>

     <p>We built and played
        <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Multi-User_Dungeon"><abbr title="Multi-User Dungeon">MUD</abbr></a>s, the text equivalent to the graphics
        intensive
        <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mmorpg"><abbr title="Massively Multiplayer Online Role-Playing Game">MMORPGs</abbr></a> of today.
        We taught ourselves UNIX and networking. We even managed to get the
        municipality to allow us an aerial fiber cable across the street
        (fun day playing at the roof of the municipal building). With it,
        we became one of the first places in town with Internet access.</p>

     <p>The day finally came when I moved out and headed to the university.
     <aside><img src="images/geekdom/umu.jpg"
       alt="UmeÃ¥ University"></aside>
        With a 10 Mbit/s internet pipe fed into my dorm room, life was good.
        Given the density of like-minded people, I was bound to make friends.
        I still hang out with a lot of them. The quality of the courses was
        with few exceptions very good and I learned a lot that has come in
        handy during the course of my professional life.</p>

     <p>Anything worth doing is worth overdoing - words to live by. Computer
        lab excercises tended to have an underwhelming scope. A simple dice
        game excercise with trivial AI quickly gets improved with a network
        protocol, chat (including AI chat) and the possibility to cheat. A
        bit of sleep traded for an extra challenge, a fun way of learning a
        little more. I recall an element of competition was involved.</p>

     <p>The <a href="http://www.acc.umu.se/">Academic Computer Club</a>
        proved to be more than a social venue and a cheap service provider
        for email and web hosting.
        <aside><img src="images/geekdom/acc.svg"
          alt="ACC - formerly known as TSDF"></aside>
        Taking an active part in the club as board member and sysadmin
        allowed me to learn a great deal about UNIX administration,
        free and open source software and the running of a society.
        Since my first employments were in the city, I remained an
        active member. To this day, I still have a token presence.</p>

     <p>One of the highlights of my post graduate years at the
        university was building a
        <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Top_500">Top 500</a>
        <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Supercomputer">supercomputer</a>.
        We built 120 linux boxes with a really fast
        <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dolphin_Interconnect_Solutions">interconnect</a>.
